text: July 13, 1490 – John of Kastav finishes a cycle of frescoes in the Holy Trinity Church in Hrastovlje [now southwestern Slovenia].
July 13, 1573 – Eighty Yearsʼ War: The Siege of Haarlem ends after seven months.
July 13, 1814 – The Carabinieri, the national gendarmerie of Italy, is established.
July 13, 1249 – Coronation of Alexander III as King of Scots.
July 13, 1941 – World War II: Montenegrins begin a popular uprising against the Axis powers [ʼʼTrinaestojulski ustanakʼʼ].
July 13, 1794 – The Battle of the Vosges is fought between French forces and those of Prussia and Austria.
July 13, 1977 – Somalia declares war on Ethiopia, starting the Ethiopian-Somali War.
July 12, 1561 – Saint Basilʼs Cathedral in Moscow is consecrated.
July 12, 1691 – Battle of Aughrim [Julian calendar]: The decisive victory of William III of Englandʼs forces in Ireland.
July 12, 1967 – The Newark riots begin in Newark, New Jersey.
July 12, 1799 – Ranjit Singh conquers Lahore and becomes Maharaja of the Punjab [Sikh Empire].
July 12, 1562 – Fray Diego de Landa, acting Bishop of Yucatán, burns the sacred books of the Maya.
July 12, 1862 – The Medal of Honor is authorized by the United States Congress.
July 12, 1493 – Hartmann Schedelʼs ʼʼNuremberg Chronicleʼʼ, one of the best-documented early printed books, is published.
July 12, 1806 – Liechtenstein is given full sovereignty after its accession to the Confederation of the Rhine.
July 12, 1989 – Lotte World Adventure opened in Seoul, South Korea.
July 12, 1191 – Third Crusade: Saladinʼs garrison surrenders to Philip Augustus, ending the two-year siege of Acre.
July 12, 1962 – The Rolling Stones perform their first concert, at the Marquee Club in London, England, United Kingdom.
July 12, 1527 – Lê Cung Hoàng ceded the throne to Mạc Đăng Dung, ending the Lê Dynasty and starting the Mạc Dynasty.
July 11, 1979 – Americaʼs first space station, ʼʼSkylabʼʼ, is destroyed as it re-enters the Earthʼs atmosphere over the Indian Ocean.
July 11, 1740 – Pogrom: Jews are expelled from Little Russia.
July 11, 1922 – The Hollywood Bowl opens.
July 11, 1750 – Halifax, Nova Scotia is almost completely destroyed by fire.
July 11, 1174 – Baldwin IV, 13, becomes King of Jerusalem, with Raymond III, Count of Tripoli as regent and William of Tyre as chancellor.
July 11, 1616 – Samuel de Champlain returns to Quebec.
July 11, 1882 – The British Mediterranean Fleet begins the Bombardment of Alexandria in Egypt as part of the Anglo-Egyptian War.
July 11, 1476 – Giuliano della Rovere is appointed bishop of Coutances.
July 11, 1960 – Congo Crisis: The State of Katanga breaks away from the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
July 11, 1971 – Copper mines in Chile are nationalized.
July 11, 1848 – Waterloo railway station in London opens.
July 10, 1877 – The then-villa of Mayagüez, Puerto Rico, formally receives its city charter from the Royal Crown of Spain.
July 10, 1973 – The Bahamas gain full independence within the Commonwealth of Nations.
July 10, 1940 – World War II: The Vichy government is established in France.
July 10, 1976 – One American and three British mercenaries are executed in Angola following the Luanda Trial.
July 10, 1938 – Howard Hughes sets a new record by completing a 91-hour airplane flight around the world.
July 10, 1978 – President Moktar Ould Daddah of Mauritania is ousted in a bloodless coup dʼétat.
July 10, 1946 – Hungarian hyperinflation sets a record with inflation of 348.46 percent per day, or prices doubling every eleven hours.
July 10, 1850 – U.S. President Millard Fillmore is sworn in, a day after becoming President upon Zachary Taylorʼs death.
July 10, 1991 – The South African cricket team is readmitted into the International Cricket Council following the end of Apartheid.
July 10, 1212 – The most severe of several early fires of London burns most of the city to the ground.
July 10, 1942 – Diplomatic relations between the Netherlands and the Soviet Union are established.
July 10, 1973 – National Assembly of Pakistan passes a resolution on the recognition of Bangladesh.
July 9, 1701 – War of the Spanish Succession: Austrians defeat France in the Battle of Carpi.
July 9, 2011 – South Sudan gains independence and secedes from Sudan.
July 9, 1863 – American Civil War: The Siege of Port Hudson ends.
July 9, 1962 – The Starfish Prime high-altitude nuclear test is conducted by the United States.
July 9, 1810 – Napoleon annexes the Kingdom of Holland as part of the First French Empire.
July 9, 1972 – The Troubles: In Belfast, British Army snipers shoot five civilians dead in the Springhill Massacre.
July 9, 1877 – The inaugural Wimbledon Championships begins.
July 9, 1540 – King Henry VIII of England annuls his marriage to his fourth wife, Anne of Cleves.
July 9, 1944 – World War II: Battle of Normandy: British and Canadian forces capture Caen, France.
July 9, 1790 – Russo-Swedish War: Second Battle of Svensksund: In the Baltic Sea, the Swedish Navy captures one third of the Russian fleet.
July 9, 1986 – The Parliament of New Zealand passes the Homosexual Law Reform Act legalising homosexuality in New Zealand.
July 9, 1999 – Days of student protests begin after Iranian police and hardliners attack a student dormitory at the University of Tehran.
July 8, 1859 – King Charles XV & IV accedes to the throne of Sweden–Norway.
July 8, 1889 – The first issue of ʼʼThe Wall Street Journalʼʼ is published.
July 8, 1932 – The Dow Jones Industrial Average reaches its lowest level of the Great Depression, closing at 41.22.
July 8, 1994 – Kim Jong-il begins to assume supreme leadership of North Korea upon the death of his father, Kim Il-sung.
July 8, 1808 – Joseph Bonaparte approves the Bayonne Statute, a royal charter intended as the basis for his rule as king of Spain.
July 8, 1822 – Chippewas turn over a huge tract of land in Ontario to the United Kingdom.
July 8, 2011 – Space Shuttle Atlantis is launched in the final mission of the U.S. Space Shuttle program.
July 8, 1968 – The Chrysler wildcat strike begins in Detroit, Michigan.
July 8, 1966 – King Mwambutsa IV Bangiriceng of Burundi is deposed by his son Prince Charles Ndizi.
July 8, 1760 – French and Indian War: Battle of Restigouche: British forces defeat French forces in last naval battle in New France.
July 8, 1948 – The United States Air Force accepts its first female recruits into a program called Women in the Air Force [WAF].
July 8, 1874 – The Mounties begin their March West.
July 7, 1124 – Tyre falls to the Crusaders.
July 7, 1892 – Katipunan: The Revolutionary Philippine Brotherhood is established, contributing to the fall of the Spanish Empire in Asia.
July 7, 1898 – U.S. President William McKinley signs the Newlands Resolution annexing Hawaii as a territory of the United States.
July 6, 1966 – Malawi becomes a republic, with Hastings Banda as its first President.
July 6, 1535 – Sir Thomas More is executed for treason against King Henry VIII of England.
July 6, 1630 – Thirty Yearsʼ War: Four thousand Swedish troops under Gustavus Adolphus land in Pomerania, Germany.
July 6, 1957 – John Lennon and Paul McCartney meet for the first time, as teenagers at Woolton Fete, three years before forming the Beatles.
July 6, 2006 – The Nathu La pass between India and China, sealed during the Sino-Indian War, re-opens for trade after 44 years.
July 6, 1975 – The Comoros declares independence from France.
July 6, 1885 – Louis Pasteur successfully tests his vaccine against rabies on Joseph Meister, a boy who was bitten by a rabid dog.
July 6, 1573 – French Wars of Religion: Siege of La Rochelle ends.
July 6, 1801 – First Battle of Algeciras: Outnumbered French Navy ships defeat the Royal Navy in the fortified Spanish port of Algeciras.
July 5, 1934 – "Bloody Thursday": Police opens fire on striking longshoremen in San Francisco.
July 5, 1940 – World War II: The United Kingdom and the Vichy France government break off diplomatic relations.
July 5, 1833 – Admiral Charles Napier vanquishes the navy of the Portuguese usurper Dom Miguel at the third Battle of Cape St. Vincent.
July 5, 1954 – Elvis Presley records his first single, "Thatʼs All Right," at Sun Records in Memphis, Tennessee.
July 5, 1950 – Korean War: Task Force Smith: American and North Korean forces first clash, in the Battle of Osan.
July 5, 1316 – The Burgundian and Majorcan claimants of the Principality of Achaea meet in the Battle of Manolada
July 5, 1946 – The bikini goes on sale after debuting during an outdoor fashion show at the Molitor Pool in Paris, France.
July 5, 1884 – Germany takes possession of Cameroon.
July 5, 1948 – National Health Service Acts creates the national public health systems in the United Kingdom.
July 5, 1999 – U.S. President Bill Clinton imposes trade and economic sanctions against the Taliban regime in Afghanistan.
July 5, 1941 – World War II: Operation Barbarossa: German troops reach the Dnieper River.
July 5, 2012 – The Shard in London is inaugurated as the tallest building in Europe, with a height of 310 metres [1,020 ft].
July 4, 1886 – The people of France offer the Statue of Liberty to the people of the United States.
July 4, 836 – ʼʼPactum Sicardiʼʼ, a peace treaty between the Principality of Benevento and the Duchy of Naples, is signed.
July 4, 2004 – The cornerstone of the Freedom Tower is laid on the site of the World Trade Center in New York City.
July 4, 1994 – Rwandan Genocide: Kigali, the Rwandan capital, is captured by the Rwandan Patriotic Front, ending the genocide in the city.
July 4, 1982 – Four Iranian diplomats are abducted by Lebanese militia in Lebanon.
July 4, 1918 – Ottoman sultan Mehmed VI ascends to the throne.
July 4, 1837 – Grand Junction Railway, the worldʼs first long-distance railway, opens between Birmingham and Liverpool.
July 4, 1817 – In Rome, New York, construction on the Erie Canal begins.
July 4, 1934 – Leo Szilard patented the chain-reaction design for the atomic bomb.
July 4, 362 BC – Battle of Mantinea: The Thebans, led by Epaminondas, defeated the Spartans.
July 4, 1887 – The founder of Pakistan, Quaid-i-Azam Muhammad Ali Jinnah, joins Sindh-Madrasa-tul-Islam, Karachi.
July 4, 1951 – A court in Czechoslovakia sentences American journalist William N. Oatis to ten years in prison on charges of espionage.
July 3, 1852 – Congress establishes the United Statesʼ 2nd mint in San Francisco.
July 3, 1849 – The French enter Rome in order to restore Pope Pius IX to power. This would prove a major obstacle to Italian unification.
July 3, 324 – Battle of Adrianople: Constantine I defeats Licinius, who flees to Byzantium.
July 3, 1608 – Québec City is founded by Samuel de Champlain.
July 3, 1775 – American Revolutionary War: George Washington takes command of the Continental Army at Cambridge, Massachusetts.
July 3, 1886 – Karl Benz officially unveils the Benz Patent Motorwagen: The first purpose-built automobile.
July 3, 1884 – Dow Jones & Company publishes its first stock average.
July 3, 1819 – The Bank of Savings in New York City, the first savings bank in the United States, opens.
July 3, 1863 – American Civil War: The final day of the Battle of Gettysburg culminates with Pickettʼs Charge.
July 3, 1979 – U.S. President Jimmy Carter signs the first directive for secret aid to the opponents of the pro-Soviet regime in Kabul.
July 3, 1996 – Stone of Scone is returned to Scotland.
July 2, 1962 – The first Wal-Mart store opens for business in Rogers, Arkansas.
July 2, 1698 – Thomas Savery patents the first steam engine.
July 2, 1839 – Twenty miles off the coast of Cuba, 53 rebelling African slaves led by Joseph Cinqué take over the slave ship ʼʼAmistadʼʼ.
July 2, 1897 – Italian scientist Guglielmo Marconi obtains a patent for radio in London.
July 2, 1555 – The Ottoman Admiral Turgut Reis sacks the Italian city of Paola.
July 2, 963 – The imperial army proclaims Nikephoros II Phokas Emperor of the Romans on the plains outside Cappadocian Caesarea.
July 2, 1900 – The first Zeppelin flight takes place on Lake Constance near Friedrichshafen, Germany.
July 2, 1917 – The East St. Louis riots end.
July 2, 1298 – The Battle of Göllheim is fought between Albert I of Habsburg and Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg.
July 2, 1613 – The first English expedition from Massachusetts against Acadia led by Samuel Argall takes place.
July 2, 1976 – Fall of the Republic of Vietnam; Communist North Vietnam declares their union to form the Socialist Republic of Vietnam.
July 2, 2013 – The International Astronomical Union names Plutoʼs fourth and fifth moons, Kerberos and Styx.
July 1, 1997 – China resumes sovereignty over the city-state of Hong Kong, ending 156 years of British colonial rule.
July 1, 1968 – The Nuclear non-proliferation treaty is signed in Washington, D.C., London and Moscow by sixty-two countries.
July 1, 1966 – The first color television transmission in Canada takes place from Toronto.
July 1, 1863 – Keti Koti [Emancipation Day] in Suriname, marking the abolition of slavery by the Netherlands.
July 1, 1931 – United Airlines begins service [as Boeing Air Transport].
July 1, 1837 – A system of civil registration of births, marriages and deaths is established in England and Wales.
July 1, 1881 – General Order 70, the culmination of the Cardwell and Childers reforms of the British Army, comes into effect.
July 1, 1962 – Independence of Rwanda.
July 1, 1957 – The International Geophysical Year begins.
July 1, 1923 – The Canadian Parliament suspends all Chinese immigration.
July 1, 1976 – Portugal grants autonomy to Madeira.
July 1, 1962 – Independence of Burundi.
June 30, 1917 – World War I: Greece declares war on the Central Powers.
June 30, 1934 – The Night of the Long Knives, Adolf Hitlerʼs violent purge of his political rivals in Germany, takes place.
June 30, 1985 – Thirty-nine American hostages from the hijacked TWA Flight 847 are freed in Beirut after being held for 17 days.
June 30, 1986 – The U.S. Supreme Court rules in ʼʼBowers v. Hardwickʼʼ that states can outlaw homosexual acts between consenting adults.
June 30, 1944 – World War II: The Battle of Cherbourg ends with the fall of the strategically valuable port to American forces.
June 30, 1921 – U.S. President Warren G. Harding appoints former President William Howard Taft Chief Justice of the United States.
June 30, 1882 – Charles J. Guiteau is hanged in Washington, D.C. for the assassination of U.S. President James Garfield.
June 30, 1651 – The Deluge: Khmelnytsky Uprising – the Battle of Berestechko ends with a Polish victory.
June 30, 1422 – Battle of Arbedo between the duke of Milan and the Swiss cantons.
June 30, 1892 – The Homestead Strike begins near Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
June 30, 763 – The Byzantine army of emperor Constantine V defeats the Bulgarian forces in the Battle of Anchialus.
June 30, 1953 – The first Chevrolet Corvette rolls off the assembly line in Flint, Michigan.
June 29, 1915 – The North Saskatchewan River flood of 1915 is the worst flood in Edmonton history.
June 29, 1976 – The Conference of Communist and Workers Parties of Europe convenes in East Berlin
June 29, 1995 – Space Shuttle program: STS-71 Mission [ʼʼAtlantisʼʼ] docks with the Russian space station ʼʼMirʼʼ for the first time.
June 29, 1945 – Carpathian Ruthenia is annexed by the Soviet Union.
June 29, 1895 – Doukhobors burn their weapons as a protest against conscription by the Tsarist Russian government.
June 29, 1956 – The Federal Aid Highway Act of 1956 is signed, officially creating the United States Interstate Highway System.
June 29, 2012 – The June 2012 North American derecho event occurs causing widespread damage from the midwest to the mid-Atlantic states.
June 29, 1807 – Russo-Turkish War: Admiral Dmitry Senyavin destroys the Ottoman fleet in the Battle of Athos.
June 29, 1916 – The Irish Nationalist and British diplomat Roger Casement is sentenced to death for his part in the Easter Rising.
June 29, 1926 – Arthur Meighen returns to office as Prime Minister of Canada.
June 29, 1776 – First privateer battle of the American Revolutionary War fought at Turtle Gut Inlet near Cape May, New Jersey
June 29, 1786 – Alexander Macdonell and over five hundred Roman Catholic highlanders leave Scotland to settle in Glengarry County, Ontario.
June 28, 1940 – Romania cedes Bessarabia [current-day Moldova] to the Soviet Union after facing an ultimatum.
June 28, 1964 – Malcolm X forms the Organization of Afro-American Unity.
June 28, 1895 – El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua form the Greater Republic of Central America.
June 28, 1976 – The Angolan court sentences US and UK mercenaries to death sentences and prison terms in the Luanda Trial.
June 28, 1967 – Israel annexes East Jerusalem.
June 28, 1881 – Secret treaty between Austria and Serbia.
June 28, 1997 – Holyfield–Tyson II: Mike Tyson is disqualified in the 3rd round for biting a piece off Evander Holyfieldʼs ear.
June 28, 1992 – The Constitution of Estonia is signed into law.
June 28, 1950 – Korean War: North Korean Army conducted Seoul National University Hospital Massacre.
June 28, 1882 – The Anglo-French Convention of 1882 marks the territorial boundaries between Guinea and Sierra Leone.
June 28, 1996 – The Constitution of Ukraine is signed into law.
June 28, 1859 – The first conformation dog show is held in Newcastle-upon-Tyne, England.
June 27, 1954 – The Obninsk Nuclear Power Plant, the Soviet Unionʼs first nuclear power station, opens in Obninsk, near Moscow.
June 27, 1759 – General James Wolfe begins the siege of Quebec.
June 27, 1941 – German troops capture the city of Białystok during Operation Barbarossa.
June 27, 1974 – U.S. president Richard Nixon visits the Soviet Union.
June 27, 1556 – The thirteen Stratford Martyrs are burned at the stake near London for their Protestant beliefs.
June 27, 1985 – U.S. Route 66 is officially removed from the United States Highway System.
June 27, 1898 – The first solo circumnavigation of the globe is completed by Joshua Slocum from Briar Island, Nova Scotia.
June 27, 1497 – Cornish rebels Michael An Gof and Thomas Flamank are executed at Tyburn, London, England.
June 27, 1976 – Air France Flight 139 [Tel Aviv-Athens-Paris] is hijacked en route to Paris by the PLO and redirected to Entebbe, Uganda.
June 27, 1973 – The President of Uruguay Juan María Bordaberry dissolves Parliament and establishes a dictatorship.
June 27, 2007 – Tony Blair resigns as British Prime Minister, a position he had held since 1997.
June 27, 1950 – The United States decides to send troops to fight in the Korean War.
June 26, 1967 – Karol Wojtyła [later John Paul II] made a cardinal by Pope Paul VI.
June 26, 1243 – Mongols defeat the Seljuk Turks at the Battle of Köse Dağ.
June 26, 1955 – The South African Congress Alliance adopts the Freedom Charter at the Congress of the People in Kliptown.
June 26, 2006 – Mari Alkatiri, the first Prime Minister of East Timor, resigns after weeks of political unrest.
June 26, 1953 – Lavrentiy Beria, head of MVD, is arrested by Nikita Khrushchev and other members of the Politburo.
June 26, 1857 – The first investiture of the Victoria Cross in Hyde Park, London.
June 26, 1723 – After a siege and bombardment by cannon, Baku surrenders to the Russians.
June 26, 1407 – Ulrich von Jungingen becomes Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights.
June 26, 687 – Pope Benedict II chosen.
June 26, 2004 – Ólafur Ragnar Grímsson is re-elected as President of Iceland.
June 26, 1917 – The first U.S. troops arrive in France to fight alongside Britain and France against Germany in World War I.
June 26, 1843 – Treaty of Nanking comes into effect, Hong Kong Island is ceded to the British "in perpetuity".
June 25, 1949 – ʼʼLong-Haired Hareʼʼ, starring Bugs Bunny, is released in theaters.
June 25, 1658 – Spanish forces fail to retake Jamaica at the Battle of Rio Nuevo during the Anglo-Spanish War.
June 25, 1993 – Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action is adopted by World Conference on Human Rights.
